1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,659
In the autumn of 1994,

2
00:00:01,659 --> 00:00:03,242
a woman opened a dead

3
00:00:03,242 --> 00:00:04,901
man's pocket watch and

4
00:00:04,901 --> 00:00:06,559
found a letter inside.

5
00:00:06,559 --> 00:00:08,284
It had been written fifty

6
00:00:08,284 --> 00:00:09,250
years earlier,

7
00:00:09,250 --> 00:00:10,561
on the night before

8
00:00:10,561 --> 00:00:10,975
D-Day.

9
00:00:10,975 --> 00:00:12,700
The words were beautiful.

10
00:00:12,700 --> 00:00:13,942
The penmanship was

11
00:00:13,942 --> 00:00:14,494
elegant.

12
00:00:14,494 --> 00:00:16,012
And the last two lines

13
00:00:16,012 --> 00:00:17,323
were smudged beyond

14
00:00:17,323 --> 00:00:17,873
reading.

15
00:00:17,873 --> 00:00:19,761
The soldier survived the

16
00:00:19,761 --> 00:00:21,177
war. He came home.

17
00:00:21,177 --> 00:00:23,065
He married someone else.

18
00:00:23,065 --> 00:00:25,033
He never sent the letter.

19
00:00:25,033 --> 00:00:26,678
Why would a man carry a

20
00:00:26,678 --> 00:00:28,180
love letter for fifty

21
00:00:28,180 --> 00:00:29,895
years and never mail it?

22
00:00:29,895 --> 00:00:31,518
This is "Words I Never

23
00:00:31,518 --> 00:00:31,961
Said."

24
00:00:31,961 --> 00:00:33,072
On a gray October

25
00:00:33,072 --> 00:00:33,595
morning,

26
00:00:33,595 --> 00:00:35,098
Sophie Bennett stood at

27
00:00:35,098 --> 00:00:36,601
her grandfather's grave

28
00:00:36,601 --> 00:00:37,908
and realized she had

29
00:00:37,908 --> 00:00:39,409
never really known him.

30
00:00:39,409 --> 00:00:40,529
Thomas Bennett.

31
00:00:40,529 --> 00:00:41,799
Eighty years old.

32
00:00:41,799 --> 00:00:42,695
A carpenter.

33
00:00:42,695 --> 00:00:44,263
A quiet man who built

34
00:00:44,263 --> 00:00:46,130
things with his hands and

35
00:00:46,130 --> 00:00:47,624
kept everything else

36
00:00:47,624 --> 00:00:49,417
locked inside his chest.

37
00:00:49,417 --> 00:00:50,776
He didn't want a fuss.

38
00:00:50,776 --> 00:00:52,259
Said just put him in the

39
00:00:52,259 --> 00:00:53,433
ground next to your

40
00:00:53,433 --> 00:00:54,174
grandmother.

41
00:00:54,174 --> 00:00:55,319
After the service,

42
00:00:55,319 --> 00:00:56,782
Richard handed Sophie a

43
00:00:56,782 --> 00:00:57,036
key.

44
00:00:57,036 --> 00:00:58,308
"Someone has to sort

45
00:00:58,308 --> 00:00:59,517
through his things.

46
00:00:59,517 --> 00:01:00,472
I can't do it."

47
00:01:00,472 --> 00:01:01,816
Sophie took the key.

48
00:01:01,816 --> 00:01:03,160
She had things she'd

49
00:01:03,160 --> 00:01:04,773
never said to him either

50
00:01:04,773 --> 00:01:06,318
— visits she'd skipped,

51
00:01:06,318 --> 00:01:07,796
calls she'd cut short.

52
00:01:07,796 --> 00:01:09,409
Maybe that's why the key

53
00:01:09,409 --> 00:01:10,349
felt so heavy.

54
00:01:10,349 --> 00:01:12,286
Tom's attic smelled of

55
00:01:12,286 --> 00:01:14,047
sawdust and decades.

56
00:01:14,047 --> 00:01:15,896
In a cigar box tucked

57
00:01:15,896 --> 00:01:17,833
behind Army blankets —

58
00:01:17,833 --> 00:01:19,155
a pocket watch.

59
00:01:19,155 --> 00:01:19,630
Brass,

60
00:01:19,630 --> 00:01:21,450
worn smooth by years of

61
00:01:21,450 --> 00:01:23,191
handling. On the back,

62
00:01:23,191 --> 00:01:24,853
two sets of initials:

63
00:01:24,853 --> 00:01:25,724
T.B. & E.P.

64
00:01:25,724 --> 00:01:26,990
Thomas Bennett —

65
00:01:26,990 --> 00:01:28,810
and someone who was not

66
00:01:28,810 --> 00:01:30,077
her grandmother.

67
00:01:30,077 --> 00:01:32,097
Sophie pressed the clasp.

68
00:01:32,097 --> 00:01:33,874
Behind the back plate,

69
00:01:33,874 --> 00:01:35,571
folded so thin it had

70
00:01:35,571 --> 00:01:37,187
molded to the metal,

71
00:01:37,187 --> 00:01:38,884
was a single sheet of

72
00:01:38,884 --> 00:01:40,177
paper. A letter.

73
00:01:40,177 --> 00:01:41,469
Yellow with age.

74
00:01:41,469 --> 00:01:43,089
The handwriting was

75
00:01:43,089 --> 00:01:43,771
elegant.

76
00:01:43,771 --> 00:01:45,390
Almost too elegant.

77
00:01:45,390 --> 00:01:46,704
"My dearest Eleanor.

78
00:01:46,704 --> 00:01:48,018
I am writing this by

79
00:01:48,018 --> 00:01:49,398
candlelight in a tent

80
00:01:49,398 --> 00:01:51,041
that leaks when it rains.

81
00:01:51,041 --> 00:01:52,421
Tomorrow we cross the

82
00:01:52,421 --> 00:01:52,947
Channel.

83
00:01:52,947 --> 00:01:54,459
I don't know what waits

84
00:01:54,459 --> 00:01:55,708
for us on the other

85
00:01:55,708 --> 00:01:56,103
side."

86
00:01:56,103 --> 00:01:58,063
The letter spoke of walks

87
00:01:58,063 --> 00:01:59,944
along the English coast.

88
00:01:59,944 --> 00:02:01,747
Of a promise made under

89
00:02:01,747 --> 00:02:02,217
stars.

90
00:02:02,217 --> 00:02:03,941
But the last two lines

91
00:02:03,941 --> 00:02:04,960
were ruined —

92
00:02:04,960 --> 00:02:06,684
the ink smeared beyond

93
00:02:06,684 --> 00:02:07,312
reading.

94
00:02:07,312 --> 00:02:09,091
Sophie called her father.

95
00:02:09,091 --> 00:02:09,401
Dad,

96
00:02:09,401 --> 00:02:11,105
who is Eleanor Parish?

97
00:02:11,105 --> 00:02:12,023
Put it back.

98
00:02:12,023 --> 00:02:13,783
Don't mention that name

99
00:02:13,783 --> 00:02:14,243
again.

100
00:02:14,243 --> 00:02:15,069
He hung up.

101
00:02:15,069 --> 00:02:16,571
And Sophie knew this

102
00:02:16,571 --> 00:02:18,448
letter was the reason her

103
00:02:18,448 --> 00:02:19,950
grandfather had been

104
00:02:19,950 --> 00:02:21,377
quiet all his life.

105
00:02:21,377 --> 00:02:22,613
Sophie drove to her

106
00:02:22,613 --> 00:02:23,589
father's house.

107
00:02:23,589 --> 00:02:25,150
Richard sat in the dark,

108
00:02:25,150 --> 00:02:26,321
a glass of whiskey

109
00:02:26,321 --> 00:02:26,970
untouched.

110
00:02:26,970 --> 00:02:28,925
His last words, Dad.

111
00:02:28,925 --> 00:02:31,271
What were Grandpa's last

112
00:02:31,271 --> 00:02:31,857
words?

113
00:02:31,857 --> 00:02:32,894
He said...

114
00:02:32,894 --> 00:02:35,073
'Tell her I'm sorry.'

115
00:02:35,073 --> 00:02:36,016
Tell who?

116
00:02:36,016 --> 00:02:37,494
Her name was Eleanor

117
00:02:37,494 --> 00:02:39,267
Parish. A British nurse.

118
00:02:39,267 --> 00:02:40,818
He met her in England

119
00:02:40,818 --> 00:02:41,778
before D-Day.

120
00:02:41,778 --> 00:02:43,477
That's all he ever told

121
00:02:43,477 --> 00:02:43,699
me.

122
00:02:43,699 --> 00:02:45,493
Sophie held the watch in

123
00:02:45,493 --> 00:02:46,315
her pocket.

124
00:02:46,315 --> 00:02:48,034
The ticking felt like a

125
00:02:48,034 --> 00:02:49,529
heartbeat — patient,

126
00:02:49,529 --> 00:02:50,128
waiting.

127
00:02:50,128 --> 00:02:51,614
She was going to find

128
00:02:51,614 --> 00:02:52,676
Eleanor Parish.

129
00:02:52,676 --> 00:02:54,375
She was going to deliver

130
00:02:54,375 --> 00:02:56,145
the words her grandfather

131
00:02:56,145 --> 00:02:56,923
never said.

132
00:02:56,923 --> 00:02:58,789
Before flying to England,

133
00:02:58,789 --> 00:03:00,207
Sophie tracked down

134
00:03:00,207 --> 00:03:01,550
George Whitfield —

135
00:03:01,550 --> 00:03:03,266
eighty-seven years old,

136
00:03:03,266 --> 00:03:05,132
Tom's closest friend from

137
00:03:05,132 --> 00:03:05,729
the war.

138
00:03:05,729 --> 00:03:07,454
Tommy Bennett. My God.

139
00:03:07,454 --> 00:03:08,316
Those two —

140
00:03:08,316 --> 00:03:09,805
Tommy and Eleanor —

141
00:03:09,805 --> 00:03:11,216
they were the only

142
00:03:11,216 --> 00:03:13,019
beautiful thing in that

143
00:03:13,019 --> 00:03:14,195
whole ugly war.

144
00:03:14,195 --> 00:03:15,504
What happened to them?

145
00:03:15,504 --> 00:03:16,787
D-Day happened.

146
00:03:16,787 --> 00:03:17,754
Then George said

147
00:03:17,754 --> 00:03:19,084
something Sophie filed

148
00:03:19,084 --> 00:03:19,809
away without

149
00:03:19,809 --> 00:03:20,655
understanding.

150
00:03:20,655 --> 00:03:22,300
Your grandfather couldn't

151
00:03:22,300 --> 00:03:23,550
write worth a damn.

152
00:03:23,550 --> 00:03:24,932
Hands made for plows,

153
00:03:24,932 --> 00:03:25,524
not pens.

154
00:03:25,524 --> 00:03:26,774
I used to write his

155
00:03:26,774 --> 00:03:28,155
letters home for him.

156
00:03:28,155 --> 00:03:29,841
The night before D-Day,

157
00:03:29,841 --> 00:03:31,307
Tom asked Eleanor to

158
00:03:31,307 --> 00:03:33,067
marry him. She said yes.

159
00:03:33,067 --> 00:03:34,313
The next morning,

160
00:03:34,313 --> 00:03:35,633
the boats left for

161
00:03:35,633 --> 00:03:36,293
Normandy.

162
00:03:36,293 --> 00:03:38,126
That was the last time he

163
00:03:38,126 --> 00:03:38,712
saw her.

164
00:03:38,712 --> 00:03:39,639
In England,

165
00:03:39,639 --> 00:03:41,156
Sophie hit a wall.

166
00:03:41,156 --> 00:03:43,264
The British Red Cross had

167
00:03:43,264 --> 00:03:45,203
no record of an Eleanor

168
00:03:45,203 --> 00:03:45,793
Parish.

169
00:03:45,793 --> 00:03:47,563
Three weeks of calls,

170
00:03:47,563 --> 00:03:49,165
two dead-end leads,

171
00:03:49,165 --> 00:03:50,935
one Eleanor Parish in

172
00:03:50,935 --> 00:03:52,958
Surrey who turned out to

173
00:03:52,958 --> 00:03:54,644
be a dentist born in

174
00:03:54,644 --> 00:03:55,067
1955.

175
00:03:55,067 --> 00:03:56,866
Then a clerk mentioned

176
00:03:56,866 --> 00:03:58,501
the bombing records.

177
00:03:58,501 --> 00:03:59,646
June 7, 1944 —

178
00:03:59,646 --> 00:04:01,526
a Luftwaffe strike on a

179
00:04:01,526 --> 00:04:02,752
field hospital.

180
00:04:02,752 --> 00:04:04,142
The casualty list

181
00:04:04,142 --> 00:04:05,858
included "E. Parish."

182
00:04:05,858 --> 00:04:07,446
She found the grave.

183
00:04:07,446 --> 00:04:08,320
Knelt down.

184
00:04:08,320 --> 00:04:10,067
Brushed away the moss.

185
00:04:10,067 --> 00:04:11,970
"Edith Parish.

186
00:04:11,970 --> 00:04:13,465
1921–1944."

187
00:04:13,465 --> 00:04:15,662
Edith. Not Eleanor.

188
00:04:15,662 --> 00:04:17,111
A different woman.

189
00:04:17,111 --> 00:04:18,560
A different nurse.

190
00:04:18,560 --> 00:04:19,929
The same initial.

191
00:04:19,929 --> 00:04:21,621
Eleanor had survived.

192
00:04:21,621 --> 00:04:23,323
At the British Red Cross

193
00:04:23,323 --> 00:04:23,961
archives,

194
00:04:23,961 --> 00:04:25,592
Sophie found the second

195
00:04:25,592 --> 00:04:26,159
mistake.

196
00:04:26,159 --> 00:04:27,861
Eleanor's file contained

197
00:04:27,861 --> 00:04:28,357
a note:

198
00:04:28,357 --> 00:04:30,129
"Informed that PFC Thomas

199
00:04:30,129 --> 00:04:31,618
Bennett was killed in

200
00:04:31,618 --> 00:04:33,248
action at Omaha Beach."

201
00:04:33,248 --> 00:04:34,505
Killed in action.

202
00:04:34,505 --> 00:04:36,205
Except Tom hadn't died.

203
00:04:36,205 --> 00:04:37,758
He'd been wounded and

204
00:04:37,758 --> 00:04:38,423
survived.

205
00:04:38,423 --> 00:04:39,914
Two clerical errors.

206
00:04:39,914 --> 00:04:41,331
Two single letters.

207
00:04:41,331 --> 00:04:42,748
In the chaos of the

208
00:04:42,748 --> 00:04:43,941
largest military

209
00:04:43,941 --> 00:04:45,507
operation in history,

210
00:04:45,507 --> 00:04:47,371
two people who loved each

211
00:04:47,371 --> 00:04:49,086
other spent fifty years

212
00:04:49,086 --> 00:04:50,801
believing the other was

213
00:04:50,801 --> 00:04:51,174
dead.

214
00:04:51,174 --> 00:04:52,451
Sophie sat in that

215
00:04:52,451 --> 00:04:53,658
archive and wept.

216
00:04:53,658 --> 00:04:55,426
Dad. Eleanor is alive.

217
00:04:55,426 --> 00:04:57,113
She's been alive this

218
00:04:57,113 --> 00:04:57,997
whole time.

219
00:04:57,997 --> 00:04:58,809
I know.

220
00:04:58,809 --> 00:04:59,439
What?

221
00:04:59,439 --> 00:05:00,478
He found out.

222
00:05:00,478 --> 00:05:02,077
About ten years ago.

223
00:05:02,077 --> 00:05:03,596
A buddy sent him an

224
00:05:03,596 --> 00:05:05,594
article. Eleanor Parish —

225
00:05:05,594 --> 00:05:07,592
alive, living in England.

226
00:05:07,592 --> 00:05:09,058
And he didn't go to her?

227
00:05:09,058 --> 00:05:10,482
Your grandmother was

228
00:05:10,482 --> 00:05:11,336
still alive.

229
00:05:11,336 --> 00:05:12,546
He loved her too.

230
00:05:12,546 --> 00:05:13,827
Not the same way —

231
00:05:13,827 --> 00:05:15,037
but he loved her.

232
00:05:15,037 --> 00:05:16,532
He couldn't break her

233
00:05:16,532 --> 00:05:18,099
heart to mend his own.

234
00:05:18,099 --> 00:05:19,924
He carried that knowledge

235
00:05:19,924 --> 00:05:20,946
for ten years.

236
00:05:20,946 --> 00:05:22,333
Knowing she was out

237
00:05:22,333 --> 00:05:22,771
there.

238
00:05:22,771 --> 00:05:24,450
Knowing he couldn't go.

239
00:05:24,450 --> 00:05:26,202
That's what finally made

240
00:05:26,202 --> 00:05:26,931
him quiet.

241
00:05:26,931 --> 00:05:28,486
Sophie looked at the

242
00:05:28,486 --> 00:05:28,952
watch.

243
00:05:28,952 --> 00:05:30,429
The ticking sounded

244
00:05:30,429 --> 00:05:31,517
different now.

245
00:05:31,517 --> 00:05:33,072
Not patient. Urgent.

246
00:05:33,072 --> 00:05:34,951
The cottage was small.

247
00:05:34,951 --> 00:05:36,830
Stone walls covered in

248
00:05:36,830 --> 00:05:37,172
ivy.

249
00:05:37,172 --> 00:05:38,709
A garden loved for

250
00:05:38,709 --> 00:05:39,392
decades.

251
00:05:39,392 --> 00:05:41,100
Sophie walked up the

252
00:05:41,100 --> 00:05:41,527
path,

253
00:05:41,527 --> 00:05:43,576
her heart in her throat.

254
00:05:43,576 --> 00:05:44,842
The door opened.

255
00:05:44,842 --> 00:05:46,029
Eleanor Parish.

256
00:05:46,029 --> 00:05:47,453
Seventy years old.

257
00:05:47,453 --> 00:05:49,273
White hair pinned back.

258
00:05:49,273 --> 00:05:50,934
Eyes the color of the

259
00:05:50,934 --> 00:05:52,199
English Channel.

260
00:05:52,199 --> 00:05:53,613
Can I help you, dear?

261
00:05:53,613 --> 00:05:55,464
Over Eleanor's shoulder,

262
00:05:55,464 --> 00:05:56,389
on the wall,

263
00:05:56,389 --> 00:05:58,240
Sophie saw a photograph.

264
00:05:58,240 --> 00:06:00,168
A young American soldier.

265
00:06:00,168 --> 00:06:02,019
The same photograph from

266
00:06:02,019 --> 00:06:02,790
the attic.

267
00:06:02,790 --> 00:06:04,639
Fifty years on her wall.

268
00:06:04,639 --> 00:06:05,628
My name is Sophie

269
00:06:05,628 --> 00:06:06,093
Bennett.

270
00:06:06,093 --> 00:06:07,489
I'm Tom's granddaughter.

271
00:06:07,489 --> 00:06:08,208
Oh my God.

272
00:06:08,208 --> 00:06:09,503
You have his eyes.

273
00:06:09,503 --> 00:06:10,997
Sophie placed the letter

274
00:06:10,997 --> 00:06:11,806
on the table.

275
00:06:11,806 --> 00:06:13,300
Eleanor unfolded it with

276
00:06:13,300 --> 00:06:14,856
the gentleness of someone

277
00:06:14,856 --> 00:06:16,350
handling a living thing.

278
00:06:16,350 --> 00:06:18,374
She read the first lines.

279
00:06:18,374 --> 00:06:20,155
Tears tracked down her

280
00:06:20,155 --> 00:06:22,178
cheeks. Then she stopped.

281
00:06:22,178 --> 00:06:23,284
This isn't Tom's

282
00:06:23,284 --> 00:06:24,114
handwriting.

283
00:06:24,114 --> 00:06:24,744
What?

284
00:06:24,744 --> 00:06:26,308
Tom's handwriting was

285
00:06:26,308 --> 00:06:27,425
terrible — big,

286
00:06:27,425 --> 00:06:28,617
crooked letters.

287
00:06:28,617 --> 00:06:29,958
This is beautiful.

288
00:06:29,958 --> 00:06:31,225
But it's not his.

289
00:06:31,225 --> 00:06:32,921
Eleanor closed her eyes.

290
00:06:32,921 --> 00:06:34,263
A memory surfaced —

291
00:06:34,263 --> 00:06:35,676
supply crates in the

292
00:06:35,676 --> 00:06:36,736
field hospital,

293
00:06:36,736 --> 00:06:38,008
labeled in elegant

294
00:06:38,008 --> 00:06:38,855
copperplate.

295
00:06:38,855 --> 00:06:40,018
George Whitfield.

296
00:06:40,018 --> 00:06:41,523
He wrote Tom's letters

297
00:06:41,523 --> 00:06:42,071
for him.

298
00:06:42,071 --> 00:06:43,617
Eleanor smiled through

299
00:06:43,617 --> 00:06:44,320
her tears.

300
00:06:44,320 --> 00:06:45,724
Tom couldn't write.

301
00:06:45,724 --> 00:06:47,424
He could build anything

302
00:06:47,424 --> 00:06:48,533
with his hands,

303
00:06:48,533 --> 00:06:50,233
but words defeated him.

304
00:06:50,233 --> 00:06:51,859
So he spoke the words,

305
00:06:51,859 --> 00:06:53,411
and George wrote them

306
00:06:53,411 --> 00:06:53,781
down.

307
00:06:53,781 --> 00:06:55,629
Every word in this letter

308
00:06:55,629 --> 00:06:57,254
came from Tom's mouth.

309
00:06:57,254 --> 00:06:58,448
Eleanor picked up a

310
00:06:58,448 --> 00:06:59,516
magnifying glass.

311
00:06:59,516 --> 00:07:00,961
Her hands trembled over

312
00:07:00,961 --> 00:07:02,533
the bottom of the letter.

313
00:07:02,533 --> 00:07:03,748
But this part —

314
00:07:03,748 --> 00:07:05,368
the last two lines —

315
00:07:05,368 --> 00:07:06,421
this IS Tom's

316
00:07:06,421 --> 00:07:07,394
handwriting.

317
00:07:07,394 --> 00:07:08,463
She read aloud,

318
00:07:08,463 --> 00:07:10,245
each word pulled from the

319
00:07:10,245 --> 00:07:11,813
blur of fifty-year-old

320
00:07:11,813 --> 00:07:12,099
ink.

321
00:07:12,099 --> 00:07:13,650
I can't write pretty

322
00:07:13,650 --> 00:07:14,115
words.

323
00:07:14,115 --> 00:07:15,899
But I love you is all I

324
00:07:15,899 --> 00:07:16,752
know. — Tom

325
00:07:16,752 --> 00:07:18,670
That was what the ink had

326
00:07:18,670 --> 00:07:19,974
hidden for half a

327
00:07:19,974 --> 00:07:20,588
century.

328
00:07:20,588 --> 00:07:22,122
Not George's poetry.

329
00:07:22,122 --> 00:07:23,196
Just Tom. Raw,

330
00:07:23,196 --> 00:07:24,040
honest Tom.

331
00:07:24,040 --> 00:07:25,651
Saying the only thing

332
00:07:25,651 --> 00:07:27,569
that mattered in the only

333
00:07:27,569 --> 00:07:28,797
way he knew how.

334
00:07:28,797 --> 00:07:30,031
He never sent it.

335
00:07:30,031 --> 00:07:31,700
Because when he woke in

336
00:07:31,700 --> 00:07:32,643
the hospital,

337
00:07:32,643 --> 00:07:34,457
they told him Eleanor was

338
00:07:34,457 --> 00:07:34,820
dead.

339
00:07:34,820 --> 00:07:36,272
And you don't mail a

340
00:07:36,272 --> 00:07:37,578
letter to a ghost.

341
00:07:37,578 --> 00:07:39,320
So he folded it into his

342
00:07:39,320 --> 00:07:40,772
watch and carried it

343
00:07:40,772 --> 00:07:42,296
against his chest for

344
00:07:42,296 --> 00:07:43,167
fifty years.

345
00:07:43,167 --> 00:07:43,823
Eleanor...

346
00:07:43,823 --> 00:07:45,398
would you have wanted to

347
00:07:45,398 --> 00:07:46,383
hear his voice?

348
00:07:46,383 --> 00:07:47,791
I've rehearsed what I

349
00:07:47,791 --> 00:07:49,199
would say to that man

350
00:07:49,199 --> 00:07:50,607
every night for fifty

351
00:07:50,607 --> 00:07:51,009
years.

352
00:07:51,009 --> 00:07:52,317
He passed away three

353
00:07:52,317 --> 00:07:52,971
weeks ago.

354
00:07:52,971 --> 00:07:54,371
Fifty years I waited.

355
00:07:54,371 --> 00:07:56,037
And I was three weeks too

356
00:07:56,037 --> 00:07:56,370
late.

357
00:07:56,370 --> 00:07:57,216
She touched the

358
00:07:57,216 --> 00:07:58,457
photograph on the wall

359
00:07:58,457 --> 00:07:59,585
with her fingertips.

360
00:07:59,585 --> 00:08:00,310
Every night,

361
00:08:00,310 --> 00:08:01,760
I said goodnight to this

362
00:08:01,760 --> 00:08:02,425
photograph.

363
00:08:02,425 --> 00:08:03,754
I told myself he could

364
00:08:03,754 --> 00:08:04,238
hear me.

365
00:08:04,238 --> 00:08:05,547
It wasn't foolish.

366
00:08:05,547 --> 00:08:07,274
No. I suppose it wasn't.

367
00:08:07,274 --> 00:08:08,486
Eleanor crossed the

368
00:08:08,486 --> 00:08:09,890
Atlantic for the first

369
00:08:09,890 --> 00:08:10,911
time at seventy.

370
00:08:10,911 --> 00:08:12,506
She stood at Tom's grave,

371
00:08:12,506 --> 00:08:13,973
the pocket watch in her

372
00:08:13,973 --> 00:08:14,356
hands.

373
00:08:14,356 --> 00:08:16,095
I got your letter, Tom.

374
00:08:16,095 --> 00:08:17,985
It only took fifty years.

375
00:08:17,985 --> 00:08:19,497
And that last line —

376
00:08:19,497 --> 00:08:20,782
in your terrible,

377
00:08:20,782 --> 00:08:22,521
beautiful handwriting —

378
00:08:22,521 --> 00:08:24,260
that's the finest thing

379
00:08:24,260 --> 00:08:25,999
anyone has ever written

380
00:08:25,999 --> 00:08:26,453
to me.

381
00:08:26,453 --> 00:08:28,291
She laughed. A small,

382
00:08:28,291 --> 00:08:30,479
clear laugh, like a bell.

383
00:08:30,479 --> 00:08:31,892
You owe me a kitchen,

384
00:08:31,892 --> 00:08:32,901
Thomas Bennett.

385
00:08:32,901 --> 00:08:34,448
A kitchen big enough to

386
00:08:34,448 --> 00:08:35,053
dance in.

387
00:08:35,053 --> 00:08:36,022
That evening,

388
00:08:36,022 --> 00:08:37,737
Eleanor handed Sophie a

389
00:08:37,737 --> 00:08:38,930
sealed envelope.

390
00:08:38,930 --> 00:08:40,646
Yellowed. Never opened.

391
00:08:40,646 --> 00:08:42,637
I wrote this on June 5th,

392
00:08:42,637 --> 00:08:43,035
1944.

393
00:08:43,035 --> 00:08:44,867
The same night he wrote

394
00:08:44,867 --> 00:08:45,186
his.

395
00:08:45,186 --> 00:08:47,177
I was going to give it to

396
00:08:47,177 --> 00:08:48,929
him when he came back.

397
00:08:48,929 --> 00:08:49,551
Inside,

398
00:08:49,551 --> 00:08:51,596
in careful handwriting:

399
00:08:51,596 --> 00:08:52,563
"Come back to me,

400
00:08:52,563 --> 00:08:53,416
Thomas Bennett.

401
00:08:53,416 --> 00:08:54,781
I don't care if it takes

402
00:08:54,781 --> 00:08:55,748
a week or a year.

403
00:08:55,748 --> 00:08:56,658
I'll be waiting.

404
00:08:56,658 --> 00:08:58,025
I'll always be waiting."

405
00:08:58,025 --> 00:08:59,047
Two letters.

406
00:08:59,047 --> 00:09:00,666
Written on the same

407
00:09:00,666 --> 00:09:01,177
night.

408
00:09:01,177 --> 00:09:02,966
Kept for fifty years.

409
00:09:02,966 --> 00:09:03,903
Never sent.

410
00:09:03,903 --> 00:09:05,947
Never received. And yet,

411
00:09:05,947 --> 00:09:06,628
somehow,

412
00:09:06,628 --> 00:09:08,503
they found each other.

413
00:09:08,503 --> 00:09:10,161
Eleanor passed away the

414
00:09:10,161 --> 00:09:11,387
following spring.

415
00:09:11,387 --> 00:09:12,468
In her cottage.

416
00:09:12,468 --> 00:09:14,054
The watch in one hand,

417
00:09:14,054 --> 00:09:15,424
Tom's letter in the

418
00:09:15,424 --> 00:09:15,857
other,

419
00:09:15,857 --> 00:09:17,371
his photograph on the

420
00:09:17,371 --> 00:09:19,173
wall — the young soldier,

421
00:09:19,173 --> 00:09:20,183
still smiling.

422
00:09:20,183 --> 00:09:22,311
Inside the watch now were

423
00:09:22,311 --> 00:09:23,332
two letters.

424
00:09:23,332 --> 00:09:24,694
Folded together.

425
00:09:24,694 --> 00:09:26,141
Finally together.

426
00:09:26,141 --> 00:09:27,726
I used to wonder why I

427
00:09:27,726 --> 00:09:29,456
flew across an ocean for

428
00:09:29,456 --> 00:09:31,041
a man I barely visited

429
00:09:31,041 --> 00:09:32,338
when he was alive.

430
00:09:32,338 --> 00:09:33,131
Now I know.

431
00:09:33,131 --> 00:09:34,572
I was delivering the

432
00:09:34,572 --> 00:09:36,085
words he never said —

433
00:09:36,085 --> 00:09:37,670
and learning to say my

434
00:09:37,670 --> 00:09:39,183
own before it was too

435
00:09:39,183 --> 00:09:39,545
late.

436
00:09:39,545 --> 00:09:41,406
My grandfather couldn't

437
00:09:41,406 --> 00:09:42,943
write pretty words.

438
00:09:42,943 --> 00:09:44,319
But he loved her.

439
00:09:44,319 --> 00:09:45,533
And she waited.

440
00:09:45,533 --> 00:09:46,747
And in the end,

441
00:09:46,747 --> 00:09:48,769
the letter found its way.
